{"title_page": "Gene Deitch", "text_new": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = 200px\n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago, Illinois]], {{nowrap|United States}}\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|17|1924|8|8}}\n| residence          = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = [[American people|American]]\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u2013?)<br>Zdenka Deitchova (n\u00e9e Najmanov\u00e1; m. 1964\u2013present)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 - April 17, 2020)<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref> was an [[Americans|American]] (children's book) illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch is known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life and career==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]], the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942, and began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, Deitch was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML />\n\nAt the beginning of his cartooning and animation career, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine  ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML />\n\n==Animation career==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nDeitch took a position at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA) and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as [[Sidney the Elephant]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> [[Gaston Le Crayon]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint  Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter of [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on CBS television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later.\n\nIn early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney\u2019s Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> When client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], Czechoslovakia, in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdena, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> During the following decade, he collaborated with Rembrandt to produce ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], as well as 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, which he has cited as the \"primary bad example of senseless violence \u2014 humor based on pain \u2014 attack and revenge \u2014 to say nothing of the tasteless use of a headless black woman stereotype house servant.\"<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch has stated that, being a \"[[United Productions of America|UPA]] man\", he was not a fan of the ''Tom and Jerry'' cartoons, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"Deitch\"/><ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; however, Deitch claims some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title=\u2018Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection\u2019 \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's short film ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'' won an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Animated Short Film|Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short composed outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of [[Krazy Kat]] for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature length animated movie version of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds. In order to not let the rights for the novel expire he asked Deitch to produce a short movie adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13 minute long animated film never intended for distribution. The film was long considered lost until it was discovered by Snyder's son and released on YouTube in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1968 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. His studio is located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were recorded. Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, while he was followed by the Communist secret police (Stb) and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nIn 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |website=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, several days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDeitch died in Prague on April 17, 2020, at the age of 95.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Gene Deitch] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] from the original on September 8, 2015.\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = 200px\n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago, Illinois]], {{nowrap|United States}}\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2020|4|17|1924|8|8}}\n| residence          = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = [[American people|American]]\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u2013?)<br>Zdenka Deitchova (n\u00e9e Najmanov\u00e1; m. 1964\u2013present)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 - April 17, 2020)<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref> is an [[Americans|American]] (children's book) illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch is known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life and career==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]], the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942, and began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, Deitch was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML />\n\nAt the beginning of his cartooning and animation career, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine  ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML />\n\n==Animation career==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nDeitch took a position at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA) and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as [[Sidney the Elephant]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> [[Gaston Le Crayon]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint  Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter of [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on CBS television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later.\n\nIn early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney\u2019s Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> When client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], Czechoslovakia, in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdena, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> During the following decade, he collaborated with Rembrandt to produce ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], as well as 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, which he has cited as the \"primary bad example of senseless violence \u2014 humor based on pain \u2014 attack and revenge \u2014 to say nothing of the tasteless use of a headless black woman stereotype house servant.\"<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch has stated that, being a \"[[United Productions of America|UPA]] man\", he was not a fan of the ''Tom and Jerry'' cartoons, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"Deitch\"/><ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; however, Deitch claims some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title=\u2018Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection\u2019 \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's short film ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'' won an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Animated Short Film|Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short composed outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of [[Krazy Kat]] for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature length animated movie version of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds. In order to not let the rights for the novel expire he asked Deitch to produce a short movie adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13 minute long animated film never intended for distribution. The film was long considered lost until it was discovered by Snyder's son and released on YouTube in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1968 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. His studio is located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were recorded. Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, while he was followed by the Communist secret police (Stb) and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nIn 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |website=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, several days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDeitch died in Prague on April 17, 2020, at the age of 95.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Gene Deitch] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] from the original on September 8, 2015.\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "name_user": "Leonis Camosos", "label": "safe", "comment": "tense change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_Deitch"}
{"title_page": "Ryan McNeil", "text_new": "{{about|the fictional character|the football player|Ryan McNeil (American football)}}\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = The Young and the Restless\n| image = Scott Reeves as Ryan.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| image2 = \n| caption2 =\n| image3 = \n| caption3 =\n| name = Ryan McNeil \n| portrayer = [[Scott Reeves]]\n| creator = [[William J. Bell]]\n| introducer = [[Edward J. Scott]]\n| years = 1991\u20132001\n| first = June 26, 1991\n| last = December 5, 2001\n| classification = [[List of previous The Young and the Restless cast members|Former, regular]]\n| books =  \n| spinoffs = \n| alias = \n| born = 1967 \n| death = November 27, 2001\n| occupation = Businessman  \n| home = \n| wife=[[Victoria Newman]] (1992\u201393)<br>[[Nina Webster]] (1994\u201398)<br>[[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Tricia Dennison|Tricia Dennison]] (1998\u20132001)\n}}\n'''Ryan McNeil''' is a fictional character from the American [[CBS Daytime]] soap opera ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''. Created by [[William J. Bell]], the character was portrayed by [[Scott Reeves]], who made his first appearance On June 26, 1991 as a businessman who wanted to \"work his way to the top of the corporation ladder\". The character gained popularity upon his relationship with [[Victoria Newman]] ([[Heather Tom]]), which initially received criticism due to the characters' [[age gap]]. He was also involved with [[Nina Webster]] ([[Tricia Cast]]) and the insane [[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Tricia Dennison McNeil|Tricia Dennison]] ([[Sabryn Genet]]).\n\nReeves, who described Ryan as a \"go-getter\" who was \"shrewd\" and a \"charmer\", found his seduction storyline with Victoria hard to \"play out\" considering her age. In October 2001, the actor announced his exit from ''The Young and the Restless'', stating it was to pursue other projects. The producers kept quiet about the storyline surrounding his exit, although confirmed that he would depart \"in a big way\". Within the story, Ryan prepared to remarry Victoria but Tricia, his ex-wife, attempted to shoot her and Ryan took two bullets and died from the injury. Throughout his time on the soap opera, Reeves became popular with fans as one of the genre's leading men, garnering multiple awards and nominations.\n\n==Casting==\nReeves first appeared as Ryan in May 1991, on contract. In March 2000, it was announced that Reeves had signed a three-year contract deal with [[Sony Pictures]], which would have furthered his portrayal until 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Genet and Reeves will return in Y&R roles |first=Lynda |last=Hirsch |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=March 27, 2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Havens |first=Candace |title=''Real transitions for several soap stars'' |date=May 21, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CKVEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t7UMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4032,2870567&dq=scott+reeves+leaving+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en |accessdate=April 14, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Durant Daily Democrat]]}}</ref> However, by August 2001, reports began to surface that Reeves had been released from his contract and would be exiting in a \"storyline-dictated\" departure, during the [[Nielsen ratings|November sweeps]] period.<ref name=\"Reeves Out\">{{cite web|last=J Kroll|first=Dan|title=Scott Reeves, Ryan out at Y&R|url=http://soapcentral.com/yr/news/2001/0917-reeves.php|publisher=Soap Central|accessdate=April 20, 2013|date=August 17, 2001}}</ref> In October, Reeves officially announced his exit from the soap opera, stating it was to pursue other projects. The producers kept quiet about his exit storyline, although stated that he would leave \"in a big way\".<ref name=\"Herald-Journal\" /> His character died on the episode dated November 27, 2001.\n\n==Character development==\n{{Quote box\n|bgcolor=LightCyan\n| quote = \"What his main goal is, is to get to the top, at anyone's expense. He'll do anything to anyone, for anyone, just so he can climb\".<ref name=\"TFOP\" />\n| source = \u2014Reeves on the character's incentives (1991)\n| width = 35em\n| align = left}}\nUpon Ryan's introduction to the series, arch-villain David Kimble had just departed, leaving the manipulative character of [[Jack Abbott (The Young and the Restless)|Jack Abbott]] ([[Peter Bergman]]) \"mellowing\". This is why Reeves was brought in, to fill the void, and portray a character which he best described as \"{{Linktext|cad}}s\". A businessman, Ryan wanted to work his way to the top of the corporation ladder.<ref name=\"TFOP\" /> While Reeves is a family man, ''[[The Toronto Star]]'' characterized Ryan as \"rake\" and a \"soap seducer\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Novakovich|first=Lilana|title=Family man plays soap seducer|journal=[[Toronto Star]]|date=October 21, 1991|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/466099331.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+21%2C+1991&author=Lilana+Novakovich&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=Family+man+plays+soap+seducer&pqatl=google|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[Star Media Group]]}}</ref> While he was still a newcomer on the series, Reeves stated he was having a \"great time\" playing the role. He described Ryan as a \"go-getter\" who was \"very shrewd\u2014and a real charmer\". \"He gets what he wants\", the actor explained to the ''[[Daily News of Los Angeles]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Soap Box|journal=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=July 7, 1991|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF61308204AD72A&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]}}</ref>\n\nMonths into the character's duration on the series, he manipulatively seduced businessman [[Victor Newman (fictional character)|Victor Newman]]'s ([[Eric Braeden]]) teenage daughter [[Victoria Newman|Victoria]] ([[Heather Tom]]). Reeves found it challenging to play out this storyline. He stated, \"You have to make up something, a situation in your mind, and play off that. I try to remember people I've known, or stories that I've heard about people who've been like [Ryan]\".<ref name=\"TFOP\" /> Eventually, Ryan and Victoria were married. Their marriage ended after Victoria's refused to consummate it due to her fear of sex, resulting in Ryan beginning an affair with [[Nina Webster]] ([[Tricia Cast]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reichardt |first=Nancy M. |title=Soap Scoops |journal=[[Gainesville Sun]] |date=June 14, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hURWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=guoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2618,3834097&dq=allintext:+ryan+and+nina+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gable|first=Donna|title=On `World,' land gets in the way of love|journal=[[USA Today]]|date=January 4, 1992|page=3|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref> The series' creator William J. Bell said that Victoria knew Nina still loved Ryan and suspected that the marriage would not last, and that \"in Victoria's mind, the threat is still there\".<ref name=\"Fear\">{{cite book|last=Gable |first=Donna |chapter='Young and the Restless' tackles a real-life fear: Sex |title=[[USA Today]] |date=September 10, 1992 |page=08.D}}</ref> Of Victoria's refusal to consummate her marriage, yet desperateness to get her husband back, ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' said, \"She's divorced, rich and hates sex. And now she wants her husband back. As soap operas go, Victoria Newman's plight [...] is standard daytime fare. But Victoria has one characteristic that many of her counterparts don't - she is only 17\".<ref name=\"Teen\">{{cite journal|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F140AFE463E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Can daytime dramas get a bigger share of the teen audience by giving more time to teen characters? |journal=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]  |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]|date=August 4, 1993 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nWhile working in the mail room at Newman Enterprises, Ryan met [[Victoria Newman]] ([[Heather Tom]]), the daughter of the company's founder and CEO, Victor Newman. The two fell in love and married to Victor's dismay, however, Victoria refused to consummate their relationship and Ryan cheated on her with Nina Webster. Victoria divorced him, and he then moved in with Nina and her son, [[Chance Chancellor|Phillip Chancellor IV]] ([[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]]), and he later married Nina out of obligation. He eventually developed genuine feelings for Nina, however, she fell in love with novelist [[Cole Howard]] ([[J. Eddie Peck]]). After Nina was rejected by him, she had a nervous breakdown causing Ryan to sleep with [[Tricia Dennison]] ([[Sabryn Genet]]). Nina then tried to commit suicide and shot herself in a struggle with Ryan, and he was arrested for her shooting. Nina suffered short term amnesia, and although she regained her memory and exonerated Ryan, they divorced. Ryan then ended up marrying Tricia, much to the disapproval of her father Keith Dennison (David Allen Brooks). However, Tricia was very jealous of Ryan's relationship with Phillip, who accused her of breaking apart his family. In desperation, Tricia stopped taking her birth control pills and they conceived a child, to which Ryan was against though warmed up to the idea. When she miscarried, Tricia saw it as her punishment for deceiving her husband.\n\nTricia then became obsessed with destroying her sister [[Megan Dennison]]'s ([[Ashley Jones]]) relationship with [[Tony Viscardi]] ([[Nick Scotti]]). She ran down Tony in Megan's driveway, in which it was suspected Tricia did intentionally. Eventually, all the Dennisons left town including Tricia, who left Ryan to move to [[London, England]]. Six months later, Tricia returned to Genoa City and asked Ryan to take her back, in which he refused as Victoria became interested in him again. Tricia turned to Carter Mills, who was really rapist [[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Matt Clark|Matt Clark]] ([[Rick Hearst]]). He used her, leading Tricia to attempt suicide but Ryan was able to stop her. After Ryan and Victoria reunited, Victor had Tricia move in with him to keep her away from them. They decided to get remarried, and on their wedding day, Tricia arrived in wedding dress identical to Victoria's, locked her in a closet and took her place at the altar, where she held Ryan at gunpoint to remarry her. Victor broke Victoria free, who entered the chapel where Tricia shot twice at her, but Ryan jumped in front to save her life. Eventually, Ryan died from the gunshot wounds, leaving Victoria devastated and alone. Shortly after, Ryan appeared to Victoria in a dream where they said their vows, and she awoke with a ring on her finger.\n\n==Reception==\nA syndicated article that appeared in ''The Fort Oglethorpe Press'' described Ryan's attempts to seduce Victoria as \"a path that's fraught with peril and which forces the good-natured actor to search hard for inspiration\".<ref name=\"TFOP\">{{cite news|title=Laid-back lad loathsome as a lout |work = The Fort Oglethorpe Press |date=November 13, 1991 |page=6 |accessdate = April 6, 2013 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=392&dat=19911113&id=lv9LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SD8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6273,1051408}}</ref> Over his duration on ''The Young and the Restless'', Reeves became popular with fans, and his performance was met with acclaim from his peers. In 1994, he garnered a [[Soap Opera Digest Award]] for Outstanding Younger Actor.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Days of our Lives' big soap winner|journal=[[The Gadsden Times]]|date=February 6, 1994|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YrwfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GtgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3083,564376&dq=scott+reeves+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en|accessdate=April 20, 2013|publisher=[[Halifax Media Group]]}}</ref> In 1997 and 1998, he earned [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nominations for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor]]. The following year, he received a Soap Opera Digest Award nomination for Best Supporting Actor.<ref name=\"popular\" /> Upon learning of the actor's decision to quit following ten years on the soap opera, ''[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]]'' said it was \"hard to believe\" that one of \"daytime's most popular young leading men are leaving the fold\".<ref name=\"Herald-Journal\">{{cite journal|last=Havens|first=Candace|title=Hunks depart; Passions scores down under|journal=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]]|date=October 21, 2001|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PD4fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EtAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4078,7185352&dq=scott+reeves+leaving+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[Pioneer News Group]]}}</ref> Fans of Reeves hoped that the show's writers would play \"the ghost card\" for him to return to the series.<ref name=\"popular\">{{cite web|last=J Kroll|first=Dan|title=Reeves returns to Y&R -- but not to work|url=http://www.soapcentral.com/yr/news/2002/0114-reeves.php|publisher=Soap Central|accessdate=April 20, 2013|date=January 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{The Young and the Restless}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNeil, Ryan}}\n[[Category:The Young and the Restless characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1991]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the fictional character|the football player|Ryan McNeil (American football)}}\n{{Infobox soap character\n| series = The Young and the Restless\n| image = Scott Reeves as Ryan.jpg\n| imagesize = 200px\n| image2 = \n| caption2 =\n| image3 = \n| caption3 =\n| name = Ryan McNeil \n| portrayer = [[Scott Reeves]]\n| creator = [[William J. Bell]]\n| introducer = [[Edward J. Scott]]\n| years = 1991\u20132001\n| first = June 26, 1991\n| last = December 5, 2001\n| classification = [[List of previous The Young and the Restless cast members|Former, regular]]\n| books =  \n| spinoffs = \n| alias = \n| born = 1967 \n| death = November 27, 2001\n| occupation = Businessman  \n| home = \n| wife=[[Victoria Newman]] (1992\u201393)<br>[[Nina Webster]] (1994\u201398)<br>[[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Tricia Dennison|Tricia Dennison]] (1998\u20132001)\n}}\n'''Ryan McNeil''' is a fictional character from the American [[CBS Daytime]] soap opera ''[[The Young and the Restless]]''. Created by [[William J. Bell]], the character was portrayed by [[Scott Reeves]], who made his first appearance On June 26, 1991 as a businessman who wanted to \"work his way to the top of the corporation ladder\". The character gained popularity upon his relationship with [[Victoria Newman]] ([[Heather Tom]]), which initially received criticism due to the characters' [[age gap]]. He was also involved with [[Nina Webster]] ([[Tricia Cast]]) and the insane [[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Tricia Dennison McNeil|Tricia Dennison]] ([[Sabryn Genet]]).\n\nReeves, who described Ryan as a \"go-getter\" who was \"shrewd\" and a \"charmer\", found his seduction storyline with Victoria hard to \"play out\" considering her age. In October 2001, the actor announced his exit from ''The Young and the Restless'', stating it was to pursue other projects. The producers kept quiet about the storyline surrounding his exit, although confirmed that he would depart \"in a big way\". Within the story, Ryan prepared to remarry Victoria but Tricia, his ex-wife, attempted to shoot her and Ryan took two bullets and died from the injury. Throughout his time on the soap opera, Reeves became popular with fans as one of the genre's leading men, garnering multiple awards and nominations.\n\n==Casting==\nReeves first appeared as Ryan in May 1991, on contract. In March 2000, it was announced that Reeves had signed a three-year contract deal with [[Sony Pictures]], which would have furthered his portrayal until 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Genet and Reeves will return in Y&R roles |first=Lynda |last=Hirsch |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |date=March 27, 2000 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Havens |first=Candace |title=''Real transitions for several soap stars'' |date=May 21, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CKVEAAAAIBAJ&sjid=t7UMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4032,2870567&dq=scott+reeves+leaving+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en |accessdate=April 14, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Durant Daily Democrat]]}}</ref> However, by August 2001, reports began to surface that Reeves had been released from his contract and would be exiting in a \"storyline dictated\" departure, during the [[Nielsen ratings|November sweeps]] period.<ref name=\"Reeves Out\">{{cite web|last=J Kroll|first=Dan|title=Scott Reeves, Ryan out at Y&R|url=http://soapcentral.com/yr/news/2001/0917-reeves.php|publisher=Soap Central|accessdate=April 20, 2013|date=August 17, 2001}}</ref> In October, Reeves officially announced his exit from the soap opera, stating it was to pursue other projects. The producers kept quiet about his exit storyline, although stated that he would leave \"in a big way\".<ref name=\"Herald-Journal\" /> His character died on the episode dated November 27, 2001.\n\n==Character development==\n{{Quote box\n|bgcolor=LightCyan\n| quote = \"What his main goal is, is to get to the top, at anyone's expense. He'll do anything to anyone, for anyone, just so he can climb\".<ref name=\"TFOP\" />\n| source = \u2014Reeves on the character's incentives (1991)\n| width = 35em\n| align = left}}\nUpon Ryan's introduction to the series, arch-villain David Kimble had just departed, leaving the manipulative character of [[Jack Abbott (The Young and the Restless)|Jack Abbott]] ([[Peter Bergman]]) \"mellowing\". This is why Reeves was brought in, to fill the void, and portray a character which he best described as \"{{Linktext|cad}}s\". A businessman, Ryan wanted to work his way to the top of the corporation ladder.<ref name=\"TFOP\" /> While Reeves is a family man, ''[[The Toronto Star]]'' characterized Ryan as \"rake\" and a \"soap seducer\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Novakovich|first=Lilana|title=Family man plays soap seducer|journal=[[Toronto Star]]|date=October 21, 1991|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/466099331.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+21%2C+1991&author=Lilana+Novakovich&pub=Toronto+Star&desc=Family+man+plays+soap+seducer&pqatl=google|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[Star Media Group]]}}</ref> While he was still a newcomer on the series, Reeves stated he was having a \"great time\" playing the role. He described Ryan as a \"go-getter\" who was \"very shrewd\u2014and a real charmer\". \"He gets what he wants\", the actor explained to the ''[[Daily News of Los Angeles]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Soap Box|journal=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]|date=July 7, 1991|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF61308204AD72A&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]}}</ref>\n\nMonths into the character's duration on the series, he manipulatively seduced businessman [[Victor Newman (fictional character)|Victor Newman]]'s ([[Eric Braeden]]) teenage daughter [[Victoria Newman|Victoria]] ([[Heather Tom]]). Reeves found it challenging to play out this storyline. He stated, \"You have to make up something, a situation in your mind, and play off that. I try to remember people I've known, or stories that I've heard about people who've been like [Ryan]\".<ref name=\"TFOP\" /> Eventually, Ryan and Victoria were married. Their marriage ended after Victoria's refused to consummate it due to her fear of sex, resulting in Ryan beginning an affair with [[Nina Webster]] ([[Tricia Cast]]).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reichardt |first=Nancy M. |title=Soap Scoops |journal=[[Gainesville Sun]] |date=June 14, 1992 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hURWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=guoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2618,3834097&dq=allintext:+ryan+and+nina+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Gable|first=Donna|title=On `World,' land gets in the way of love|journal=[[USA Today]]|date=January 4, 1992|page=3|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]}}</ref> The series' creator William J. Bell said that Victoria knew Nina still loved Ryan and suspected that the marriage would not last, and that \"in Victoria's mind, the threat is still there\".<ref name=\"Fear\">{{cite book|last=Gable |first=Donna |chapter='Young and the Restless' tackles a real-life fear: Sex |title=[[USA Today]] |date=September 10, 1992 |page=08.D}}</ref> Of Victoria's refusal to consummate her marriage, yet desperateness to get her husband back, ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' said, \"She's divorced, rich and hates sex. And now she wants her husband back. As soap operas go, Victoria Newman's plight [...] is standard daytime fare. But Victoria has one characteristic that many of her counterparts don't - she is only 17\".<ref name=\"Teen\">{{cite journal|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F140AFE463E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Can daytime dramas get a bigger share of the teen audience by giving more time to teen characters? |journal=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]  |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]|date=August 4, 1993 |accessdate=April 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Storylines==\nWhile working in the mail room at Newman Enterprises, Ryan met [[Victoria Newman]] ([[Heather Tom]]), the daughter of the company's founder and CEO, Victor Newman. The two fell in love and married to Victor's dismay, however, Victoria refused to consummate their relationship and Ryan cheated on her with Nina Webster. Victoria divorced him, and he then moved in with Nina and her son, [[Chance Chancellor|Phillip Chancellor IV]] ([[Thomas Dekker (actor)|Thomas Dekker]]), and he later married Nina out of obligation. He eventually developed genuine feelings for Nina, however, she fell in love with novelist [[Cole Howard]] ([[J. Eddie Peck]]). After Nina was rejected by him, she had a nervous breakdown causing Ryan to sleep with [[Tricia Dennison]] ([[Sabryn Genet]]). Nina then tried to commit suicide and shot herself in a struggle with Ryan, and he was arrested for her shooting. Nina suffered short term amnesia, and although she regained her memory and exonerated Ryan, they divorced. Ryan then ended up marrying Tricia, much to the disapproval of her father Keith Dennison (David Allen Brooks). However, Tricia was very jealous of Ryan's relationship with Phillip, who accused her of breaking apart his family. In desperation, Tricia stopped taking her birth control pills and they conceived a child, to which Ryan was against though warmed up to the idea. When she miscarried, Tricia saw it as her punishment for deceiving her husband.\n\nTricia then became obsessed with destroying her sister [[Megan Dennison]]'s ([[Ashley Jones]]) relationship with [[Tony Viscardi]] ([[Nick Scotti]]). She ran down Tony in Megan's driveway, in which it was suspected Tricia did intentionally. Eventually, all the Dennisons left town including Tricia, who left Ryan to move to [[London, England]]. Six months later, Tricia returned to Genoa City and asked Ryan to take her back, in which he refused as Victoria became interested in him again. Tricia turned to Carter Mills, who was really rapist [[The Young and the Restless characters (1990s)#Matt Clark|Matt Clark]] ([[Rick Hearst]]). He used her, leading Tricia to attempt suicide but Ryan was able to stop her. After Ryan and Victoria reunited, Victor had Tricia move in with him to keep her away from them. They decided to get remarried, and on their wedding day, Tricia arrived in wedding dress identical to Victoria's, locked her in a closet and took her place at the altar, where she held Ryan at gunpoint to remarry her. Victor broke Victoria free, who entered the chapel where Tricia shot twice at her, but Ryan jumped in front to save her life. Eventually, Ryan died from the gunshot wounds, leaving Victoria devastated and alone. Shortly after, Ryan appeared to Victoria in a dream where they said their vows, and she awoke with a ring on her finger.\n\n==Reception==\nA syndicated article that appeared in ''The Fort Oglethorpe Press'' described Ryan's attempts to seduce Victoria as \"a path that's fraught with peril and which forces the good-natured actor to search hard for inspiration\".<ref name=\"TFOP\">{{cite news|title=Laid-back lad loathsome as a lout |work = The Fort Oglethorpe Press |date=November 13, 1991 |page=6 |accessdate = April 6, 2013 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=392&dat=19911113&id=lv9LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SD8DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6273,1051408}}</ref> Over his duration on ''The Young and the Restless'', Reeves became popular with fans, and his performance was met with acclaim from his peers. In 1994, he garnered a [[Soap Opera Digest Award]] for Outstanding Younger Actor.<ref>{{cite journal|title='Days of our Lives' big soap winner|journal=[[The Gadsden Times]]|date=February 6, 1994|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YrwfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GtgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3083,564376&dq=scott+reeves+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en|accessdate=April 20, 2013|publisher=[[Halifax Media Group]]}}</ref> In 1997 and 1998, he earned [[Daytime Emmy Award]] nominations for [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor]]. The following year, he received a Soap Opera Digest Award nomination for Best Supporting Actor.<ref name=\"popular\" /> Upon learning of the actor's decision to quit following ten years on the soap opera, ''[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]]'' said it was \"hard to believe\" that one of \"daytime's most popular young leading men are leaving the fold\".<ref name=\"Herald-Journal\">{{cite journal|last=Havens|first=Candace|title=Hunks depart; Passions scores down under|journal=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald Journal]]|date=October 21, 2001|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PD4fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EtAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4078,7185352&dq=scott+reeves+leaving+the+young+and+the+restless&hl=en|accessdate=April 14, 2013|publisher=[[Pioneer News Group]]}}</ref> Fans of Reeves hoped that the show's writers would play \"the ghost card\" for him to return to the series.<ref name=\"popular\">{{cite web|last=J Kroll|first=Dan|title=Reeves returns to Y&R -- but not to work|url=http://www.soapcentral.com/yr/news/2002/0114-reeves.php|publisher=Soap Central|accessdate=April 20, 2013|date=January 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{The Young and the Restless}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNeil, Ryan}}\n[[Category:The Young and the Restless characters]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1991]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCasting:Punctuation for adjective form", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryan_McNeil"}
{"title_page": "Beatriz, Caguas, Puerto Rico", "text_new": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Beatriz\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              =\n| nickname                 =\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = \n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = \n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = \n| mapsize                  = \n| map_caption              = \n| image_map1               = \n| mapsize1                 = \n| map_caption1             =\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.175116800000001|-66.079121099999995|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415169|Beatriz}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|Caguas ban.jpg}} [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]]\n<!-- Politics --------------- -->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| leader_title1            = \n| leader_name1             =\n| leader_title2            =\n| leader_name2             =\n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n| established_title2       = \n| established_date2        =\n| established_title3       = \n| established_date3        =\n<!-- Area    ------------------- -->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi          =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   --------------------- -->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2010 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL -------- -->\n| population_total         = 4353\n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW -- -->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  ------------- -->\n| timezone                 = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset               = &minus;4\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = 725\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others ------ -->\n| postal_code_type         =\n| postal_code              =\n| area_code                = \n| blank_name               = \n| blank_info               = \n| blank1_name              = \n| blank1_info              = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Beatriz''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[Caguas, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 4,353.<ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBeatriz is located at the coordinates {{coord|18|10|23|N|66|4|37|W}}. According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Beatriz has a total area of 15.89&nbsp;km\u00b2, of which 15.89&nbsp;km\u00b2 is land and (0.03%) 0.01&nbsp;km\u00b2 is water.<ref name=\"2010 Census\" /> Beatriz is located in the Sierra de Cayey, an extension of [[Cordillera Central (Puerto Rico)|Cordillera Central]] mountain range.\n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2010 Census, there were 4,353 people residing in Beatriz. The population density was 27,391 inhabitants per km\u00b2. Of 4,353 inhabitants, Beatriz was composed of 68.76% Whites, 13% were Black, 0.62% were American Indian, 0.05% were Asian, 0.02% were Pacific Islanders, 12.27% were of other races and 5.28% belonged to two or more races. In all, the population was 99.47% Hispanic or Latino.<ref name=\"2010 Census\" />\n\n==History==\nThe [[United States]] took control of Puerto Rico from [[Spain]] in the aftermath of the [[Spanish-American War]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|Treaty of Paris of 1898]] and conducted its first [[census]] of Puerto Rico, finding that the population of Beatriz barrio was 868.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n253 162]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe area was mostly made up of subsistence farms in the 19th century. Botanist [[William Edwin Safford]] visited Beatriz in 1898 to document the local plant life.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=William Edwin Safford|title=Notes of a naturalist afloat|journal=American Fern Journal|date=April 1912|volume=2|issue=2|page=40}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1899 San Ciriaco hurricane]] devastated Beatriz, and many farmers began working for the newly established [[History of Puerto Rico#United States rule (1898\u2013present)|military government]] of the United States of America building roads.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Rosa E. Carrasquillo|title=Our Landless Patria: Marginal Citizenship and Race in Caguas, Puerto Rico|date=2006|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=0803215371|page=86}}</ref> At the time, a store owned by wealthy landowner Don Ram\u00f3n \u00c1lvarez was the center of economic life in Beatriz. In 1900, one of the store's cashiers Don Demetrio L\u00f3pez was elected [[alcalde]] and comisario of Beatriz.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Rosa E. Carrasquillo|title=Our Landless Patria: Marginal Citizenship and Race in Caguas, Puerto Rico|date=2006|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=0803215371|page=32}}</ref>\n\nBeatriz barrio was hit by [[Hurricane Maria]] on 20 September 2017 and many residents still did not have electricity as of March 2018, six months later.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://caguas.gov.pr/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/09.-Beatriz2014_11x17.jpg Sector map of Barrio Beatriz]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beatriz}}\n[[Category:Barrios of Caguas, Puerto Rico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Beatriz\n| other_name               =\n| native_name              =\n| nickname                 =\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n| motto                    =\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = \n| imagesize                =\n| image_caption            = \n| image_flag               = \n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = \n| seal_size                =\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = \n| mapsize                  = \n| map_caption              = \n| image_map1               = \n| mapsize1                 = \n| map_caption1             =\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.175116800000001|-66.079121099999995|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415169|Beatriz}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|Caguas ban.jpg}} [[Caguas, Puerto Rico|Caguas]]\n<!-- Politics -------------